    "docs/package-lock-management.md": "# package-lock.json Management\n\n## Why it matters\npackage-lock.json records the exact dependency versions resolved by npm. This makes installs reproducible across local development, CI, and production.\n\n## How to generate it\n- Initial creation:\n  - `npm install`\n- Regenerate without changing installed modules:\n  - `npm install --package-lock-only`\n- Clean install using the lockfile:\n  - `npm ci`\n\n## Team workflow\n1. Edit `package.json` as needed.\n2. Run `npm install` to update `package-lock.json`.\n3. Review the diff in both files.\n4. Commit both files together.\n5. Use `npm ci` in CI/CD.\n\n## Updating dependencies\n- Minor/patch updates:\n  - `npm update`\n- Specific package update:\n  - `npm install <package>@<version>`\n- After updates, inspect the resulting lockfile changes.\n\n## Best practices\n- Commit `package-lock.json`.\n- Use `npm ci` in automation.\n- Keep npm versions aligned when possible.\n- Do not hand-edit the lockfile.\n- Regenerate the lockfile after dependency changes.\n\n## Troubleshooting\n- If installs fail due to lock mismatch, run `npm install` locally, verify changes, and commit the updated lockfile.\n- If CI is not reproducible, ensure it uses `npm ci` and not `npm install`."
